IMPUTATION

A simple strategy for imputation of missing values of variable (e.g. PAYMENTS_6M) is to sample the distribution of the known values for customers with similar characteristics. A simple definition of similarity could be based on matching values of another relevant variable: for PAYMENTS_6M this latter could be PAYMENTS_3M.

We are going to impute missing values of x_6M for a customer with x_3M = n sampling the distribution of x_6M for the subset of customers with x_3M = n.

First step is the preparation of a reduced and cleaned (i.e.without NA) dataset to compute statistics of the existing values to be used for imputation. With this dataset, we compute contingency tables for pairs of matching _3M and _6M variables (e.g. CHANNEL1_3M, CHANNEL1_6M) and from these tables of probabilities for the x_6M values at a fixed x_3M value (basically normalizing each entry on a row by the sum of the counts that row).

df.clean <- main[!is.na(main$PAYMENTS_6M), grep("^[CMP].*_[36]M$", colnames(main))]

# prepares stats (tables) for "prediction" of missing values.
var_vec <- colnames(main)[grep("^[PCM].*_3M", colnames(main))] %>% gsub("_3M", "", .)
tab_list <- list()
for(var in var_vec) {
    v3M <- paste0(var, "_3M")
    v6M <- paste0(var, "_6M")
    i_str_n <- paste0(var, "_n")
    i_str_p <- paste0(var, "_p")

    tmp_t <- table(df.clean[, v3M], df.clean[, v6M])
    tmp_p <- tmp_t/matrix(rep(rowSums(tmp_t), each = ncol(tmp_t)), ncol = ncol(tmp_t), byrow = TRUE)
    tab_list[[i_str_n]] <- tmp_t
    tab_list[[i_str_p]] <- tmp_p
}

The actual imputation is done as follows:

# subset of data needing imputation
df.to_impute <- main[, grep("^[CMP].*_[36]M$", colnames(main))] %>% filter( . , is.na(PAYMENTS_6M))

set.seed(9898)
imputed_values <- list()
for(var in var_vec) {
    v3M <- paste0(var, "_3M")
    v6M <- paste0(var, "_6M")
    i_str_n <- paste0(var, "_n")
    i_str_p <- paste0(var, "_p")

    values <- as.integer(dimnames(tab_list[[i_str_n]])[[2]])
    imputed_values[[v6M]] <- sample(values, nrow(df.to_impute), replace = TRUE, tab_list[[i_str_p]]["0", ])
}
df.imputed_values <- as.data.frame(imputed_values)

main.imputed <- main
for(var in var_vec) {
    v6M <- paste0(var, "_6M")
    main.imputed[is.na(main.imputed[, v6M]), v6M] <- df.imputed_values[, v6M]
}

One last variable needs imputation, RECENT_PAYMENT, which is binary-valued. Because for all customers with RECENT_PAYMENT == NA the PAYMENTS_3M = 0, we can fill the missing values with 0s.

main.imputed$RECENT_PAYMENT[is.na(main$RECENT_PAYMENT)] <- 0

The dataset with imputed missing values is stored in the separate dataframe main.imputed.

NOTE about barplot colors: in this and all following barplots, colors are coded on the difference between the call percentage values and the base rate:

  • grey if the difference is less than \(2\sigma\), where the \(\sigma\) is that of the value not of the base rate.
  • green if the value is more than \(2\sigma\) larger than the base rate.
  • red if the value is more than \(2\sigma\) smaller than the base rate.

Variables Set #0a

The 1-st data set we modeled is the original one with the following changes:

  • Excluding variables:
    • EVENT1_30_FLAG (because constant)
  • Removing the incomplete cases (i.e.809 customers)
# "EVENT1_30_FLAG"

data0a.used_vars <- c("Call_Flag",
                     "DATE_FOR", "RTD_ST_CD", 
                     "CHANNEL1_6M", "CHANNEL2_6M", "CHANNEL3_6M", "CHANNEL4_6M", "CHANNEL5_6M", "METHOD1_6M", "PAYMENTS_6M", 
                     "CustomerSegment", "Tenure", 
                     "Age", "MART_STATUS", "GENDER", 
                     "CHANNEL1_3M", "CHANNEL2_3M", "CHANNEL3_3M", "CHANNEL4_3M", "CHANNEL5_3M", "METHOD1_3M", "PAYMENTS_3M", 
                     "RECENT_PAYMENT", 
                     "NOT_DI_3M", "NOT_DI_6M", 
                     "EVENT2_90_SUM", 
                     "LOGINS", 
                     "POLICYPURCHASECHANNEL")

data0a.df_for_fit <- main[, data0a.used_vars]
data0a.df_for_fit <- data0a.df_for_fit[complete.cases(data0a.df_for_fit), ]

data0a.seed <- 10471
set.seed(data0a.seed)
data0a.split <- sample.split(data0a.df_for_fit$Call_Flag, SplitRatio = 0.7)
data0a.train <- subset(data0a.df_for_fit, data0a.split == TRUE)
data0a.test  <- subset(data0a.df_for_fit, data0a.split == FALSE)

data0a.pkg <- list(used_vars = data0a.used_vars, 
                  df_for_fit = data0a.df_for_fit, 
                  seed = data0a.seed, 
                  split = data0a.split, 
                  train = data0a.train,
